<span class="displaytext"><b><em>"i will work with the people in this room, as i have for the past four years, to champion a federal marriage amendment to protect marriage as the union of a man and a woman. ... make no mistake: a federal amendment is the only way we can protect marriage from liberal, unelected judges."</em> – gov. (candidate full)</b> (gov. (candidate full), address to the family research council's values voter summit, 10/19/07) <p align="center"> <b>the (candidate last) vision: championing a federal marriage amendment</b> </p><p><b> <u>gov. (candidate full) will continue to fight for a federal marriage amendment: <br/></u> </b> <br/> <b>gov. (candidate full) reaffirmed his commitment to pass a federal marriage amendment at the recent values voters summit.</b> "i will work with the people in this room, as i have for the past four years, to champion a federal marriage amendment to protect marriage as the union of a man and a woman. ... make no mistake: a federal amendment is the only way we can protect marriage from liberal, unelected judges." (gov. (candidate full), address to the family research council's values voter summit, 10/19/07) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p>- <b>"as it happens, <u>only one of the leading (PARTY NAME) candidates – (candidate full) – supports a federal marriage amendment, which would constitutionally prevent marriage redefinition in the states."</u></b> (kathryn jean lopez, "marriage and the gop," <em>sacramento bee</em>, 9/14/07) </p></blockquote> <p><b> <u>gov. (candidate full) has been leading the fight to protect traditional marriage: <br/></u> </b> <br/> <b>in 2004, gov. (candidate last) called for a federal marriage amendment in testimony before the senate judiciary committee.</b> gov. (candidate last): "we need an amendment that restores and protects our societal definition of marriage, blocks judges from changing that definition and then, consistent with the principles of federalism, leaves other policy issues regarding marriage to state legislatures." (gov. (candidate full), testimony, united states senate committee on the judiciary, 6/22/04) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p>- <b>institute for marriage and public policy president maggie gallagher:</b> " <u>gov. (candidate last) was in washington, d.c., making the single most eloquent and articulate defense of our traditional understanding of marriage i have heard from an american politician."</u> (maggie gallagher, "in defense of the family," national review online, 6/25/04) </p></blockquote> <p><b>in a 2006 letter to all 100 u.s. senators, gov. (candidate last) stressed traditional marriage as "the ideal setting for nurturing and developing children."</b> gov. (candidate last): "our society, like all known civilizations in recorded history, has favored the union of a man and a woman with the special designation and benefits of marriage. in this respect, it has elevated the relationship of a legally bound man and woman over other relationships. <u>this recognizes that the ideal setting for nurturing and developing children is a home where there is a mother and a father."</u> (gov. (candidate full), letter to united states senators, 6/2/06) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p>- <b>gov. (candidate last): the state-by-state approach is wrong.</b> "some argue that our principles of federalism and local control require us to leave the issue of same sex marriage to the states, which means, as a practical matter, to state courts. such an argument denies the realities of modern life and <u>would create a chaotic patchwork of inconsistent laws throughout the country</u>. ... because of this, and because americans conduct their financial and legal lives in a united country bound by interstate institutions, <u>a national definition of marriage is necessary</u>." (gov. (candidate full), letter to united states senators, 6/2/06) </p></blockquote> <p align="center"> <b>the (PARTY NAME): "a chaotic patchwork of inconsistent laws"</b> </p><p><b> <u>the (PARTY NAME) oppose a federal marriage amendment: <br/></u> </b> <br/> <b>sen. (candidate full) (d-ny) said she was involved in "plotting strategy to beat the federal marriage amendment."</b> sen. (candidate last): "when you and i were plotting strategy to beat the federal marriage amendment, the reason we were plotting strategy is, we were worried it was going to pass." (logo network, presidential candidates forum, los angeles, ca, 8/9/07) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate full) (d-il) called the federal marriage amendment "a political ploy."</b> "today, we should take this amendment only for what it is - a political ploy designed to rally a few supporters and draw the country's attention away from this leadership's past failures and america's future challenges." (sen. (candidate full), "floor statement of senator (candidate full) on the federal marriage amendment," press release, 6/5/06) </p><p><b>former sen. (candidate last) (d-nc) said he has been "vigorously against" the federal marriage amendment.</b> (candidate last): "i don't think the federal government should be telling either states or our religious organizations what marriages they can and should bless. i don't think those are decisions that should be made by the federal government. i'm against the constitutional amendment, have been vigorously against it." ("former sen. (candidate full) participates in a roundtable discussion on gas prices," <em>cq transcriptions</em>, 5/31/07) </p><p><b> <u>the (PARTY NAME) would have 50 different state definitions of marriage: <br/></u> </b> <br/> <b>sen. (candidate last) said that states were "the appropriate place" for decisions on same-sex marriage.</b> "'the states have always determined age of marriage, other conditions and over time we've gotten rid a lot of discrimination that used to exist in marriage laws,' [(candidate last)] said. 'that's now happening. people are making decisions. civil 